Preheat your #oven{} to 200°C. Trim the @carrot{1}, then halve lengthways (no need to peel). Thinly slice widthways. Peel and grate the @garlic{1/2%clove} (or use a #garlic press{}). Pop the @panko breadcrumbs{25%g} in a #bowl{} and add the @olive oil{} for the crumb. Mix well to coat the crumbs and keep to one side. Line a #baking tray{} with #baking paper{}.

Place the @British chicken breasts{2} onto a lined baking tray and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Smear a thin layer of @mayonnaise{1} on the top side of each chicken breast. Carefully sprinkle the panko breadcrumbs over the mayo and press gently to ensure they stay on. Bake on the top shelf of your oven until the crumbs are golden and the chicken is cooked, ~{18-20%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: The chicken is cooked when it is no longer pink in the middle.

Pour the @water{} for the rice into a large #saucepan{} and bring to the boil. When boiling, stir in the @jasmine rice{150%g}, lower the heat to medium and pop a #lid{} on the pan. Cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove from the heat and set aside (still covered) for another ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve.

> TIP: The rice will finish cooking in its own steam.

Meanwhile, heat a splash of oil in another large saucepan over medium heat. Add the carrot and cook, stirring frequently until softened, ~{6-7%minutes}. Add the garlic and @mild curry powder{1} and cook for ~{1%minute} more. Meanwhile, in a #measuring jug{}, mix the @cornflour{10%g} with the @water{} for the curry until smooth. Pour the mixture into the pan and bring to the boil, stirring continuously.

Lower the heat to medium and stir in the @chicken stock powder{1/2} to dissolve. Simmer until the carrot is soft and the sauce is nice and thick, ~{7-8%minutes}, stirring frequently.

Once the chicken is ready, transfer to a #chopping board{} and allow to rest for ~{2%minutes}, then thinly slice. Fluff the rice up with a #fork{} and share between your plates. Taste the curry sauce and add salt and pepper to your liking. Place the chicken alongside the rice and pour the curry sauce over the rice, katsu style. Enjoy!